        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="roman" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="cel-Latn">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:down"/><persName><name>VENNISETL<hi rend="inverted">I</hi></name>
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:down"/><w type="formula"><unclear reason="lost">F</unclear>ILIVS</w><name><unclear reason="lost">E</unclear>RCAGN<hi rend="inverted">I</hi></name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>                                            
            <div type="apparatus">
                <p></p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                    <p>Of <persName xml:lang="cel-Latn">Vennisetlus</persName> son of <persName xml:lang="sga-Latn">Ercagnus</persName></p>
               </div>              
            <div type="commentary">
                    <p><q>The inscription consists of the "X son of Y" formula with the names in the genitive and <foreign xml:lang="la">filivs</foreign> in the nominative case</q>. VENNISETLI is a forerunner <q>of Welsh <persName xml:lang="cy">Gwynnhoedl (Gwynhoedl, Gwennoedyl</persName>, etc), a compound of *<foreign xml:lang="cy">windo-</foreign>, "white, holy", and *<foreign xml:lang="cy">saitlo-</foreign>, life. The spelling with E (VEND-, VENN-) may be due to Vulgar Latin or Irish influence, since the element turns up as VEND- both in Roman Britain and on ogam inscriptions... The name is probably British, rather than Irish, on account of the change of /nd > /nn/ (which occurred too late in Irish to be relevant here) and the un-Irish monophthongization of the second element... The composition vowel -I- instead of -O- could be British or Irish, although it is more typically Irish... ERCAGNI is the genitive of an Irish name *<persName xml:lang="sga">Ercagnas</persName> > OI <persName xml:lang="sga">Erccán</persName>... The suffix -AGN- seems to be exclusively Irish in origin. In its developed form <foreign xml:lang="sga">-án</foreign> it was borrowed into Brittonic and attached to natice stems as well</q> (Edwards 2007, 277-278).</p>
                    </div>
            <div type="bibliography">
                <listBibl>  
                <bibl><ptr target="EDW2007"/>
                    <citedRange unit="page">277-278</citedRange>
                </bibl>
                </listBibl>
            </div>
        </body>

